---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';

const title = 'JSON vs YAML: When to Use Which (with Real Examples)';
const description =
  'A practical comparison of JSON and YAML — syntax, readability, performance, tooling, and the specific cases where each format is the right choice.';
const date = '2026-04-30';
---

<Layout title={title} description={description}>
  <article class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 py-16 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
    <header class="mb-10">
      <p class="text-sm text-slate-500 dark:text-slate-400">
        <time datetime={date}>{date}</time> · 7 min read
      </p>
      <h1 class="mt-2 text-balance text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-slate-900 sm:text-5xl dark:text-white">
        JSON vs YAML: When to Use Which
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-4 text-lg text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-300">
        Both formats describe the same kinds of data, but they trade off in very different directions. Here is a
        decision guide based on real projects.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="article">
      <h2>The 30-second answer</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Use JSON</strong> when the producer or consumer is a program — APIs, browser-server traffic,
          interchange between services, log lines, anything machine-generated.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Use YAML</strong> when the producer is a human — application configs, infrastructure-as-code,
          CI pipeline definitions, Kubernetes manifests.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        The rest of this article explains <em>why</em>, with concrete examples and the pitfalls that bite teams
        who choose the wrong format.
      </p>

      <h2>Side-by-side: the same data in both formats</h2>
      <p>JSON:</p>
      <pre><code>{`{
  "service": "api",
  "port": 8080,
  "replicas": 3,
  "env": {
    "LOG_LEVEL": "info",
    "FEATURE_FLAGS": ["billing_v2", "new_search"]
  }
}`}</code></pre>
      <p>YAML:</p>
      <pre><code>{`service: api
port: 8080
replicas: 3
env:
  LOG_LEVEL: info
  FEATURE_FLAGS:
    - billing_v2
    - new_search`}</code></pre>
      <p>
        YAML is shorter and free of quotes and braces. JSON is uglier for humans but unambiguous for machines.
        That single tradeoff drives almost every other difference.
      </p>

      <h2>1. Readability and edit ergonomics</h2>
      <p>
        YAML wins clearly. Indentation maps to nesting, comments are allowed (<code># like this</code>), and there
        is far less punctuation noise. For a 200-line Kubernetes manifest, YAML is genuinely easier to read.
      </p>
      <p>
        JSON does not allow comments at all, which is a real friction point for human-edited files. People work
        around it with <code>"_comment"</code> keys, but it's a sign you should switch to YAML, JSON5, or TOML.
      </p>

      <h2>2. Strictness and parser surprises</h2>
      <p>
        YAML's flexibility is also its biggest footgun. The classic example is the "Norway problem":
      </p>
      <pre><code>{`countries:
  - NO
  - SE
  - DK`}</code></pre>
      <p>
        In YAML 1.1, <code>NO</code> parses as the boolean <code>false</code>. The fix is to quote it
        (<code>"NO"</code>) or use a YAML 1.2-compliant parser. JSON has no such ambiguity — strings are always
        quoted and types are unambiguous.
      </p>
      <p>Other YAML surprises:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><code>yes</code>, <code>no</code>, <code>on</code>, <code>off</code> may parse as booleans.</li>
        <li>Sexagesimal numbers (<code>1:30</code>) may parse as 90.</li>
        <li>Leading zeros may trigger octal interpretation.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        If you're shipping configuration to production, prefer a strict YAML 1.2 parser and quote string-y values
        defensively.
      </p>

      <h2>3. Performance</h2>
      <p>
        JSON parsers are everywhere, fast, and well-optimized. Browsers parse JSON natively. YAML parsing is
        meaningfully slower — typically 5-50x — because the grammar is far more complex. For high-throughput
        data interchange (think: log shippers, message queues, internal APIs), JSON is the obvious choice.
      </p>

      <h2>4. Tooling and ecosystem</h2>
      <p>
        Both have parsers in every major language, but JSON has a deeper toolbox: <code>jq</code> for command-line
        querying, JSON Schema for validation, JSONPath for selection, native browser support, and an ocean of
        formatters and diff tools (you can pretty-print JSON with the
        <a href="/tools/json-formatter">JSONKit Formatter</a> directly in your browser).
      </p>
      <p>
        YAML has solid tooling for editing (linters, language servers in VS Code), but the validation and
        querying ecosystem is younger.
      </p>

      <h2>5. Comments</h2>
      <p>
        YAML supports comments. JSON does not. If you find yourself wanting to annotate a file, that is a strong
        signal the file is human-edited and should probably be YAML, JSON5, TOML, or HCL.
      </p>

      <h2>6. References and anchors</h2>
      <p>
        YAML supports anchors (<code>&amp;name</code>) and aliases (<code>*name</code>) to deduplicate repeated
        chunks. This is genuinely useful in long config files but also a frequent source of confusion. JSON has
        no equivalent — you repeat yourself or compose at the application layer.
      </p>

      <h2>When each format is the right call</h2>

      <h3>Pick JSON when…</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>The producer is a program (HTTP API, log line, telemetry event).</li>
        <li>You need broad cross-language support without surprises.</li>
        <li>Performance matters (parse speed, payload size after compression).</li>
        <li>You need to round-trip through JavaScript (the browser, Node.js).</li>
        <li>You need schema validation that's well-supported (JSON Schema is mature).</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Pick YAML when…</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>The file is going to be edited by humans regularly.</li>
        <li>You need comments (Kubernetes manifests, GitHub Actions workflows, dbt configs).</li>
        <li>Brevity matters more than throughput.</li>
        <li>You want anchors/aliases to keep configs DRY.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Converting between them</h2>
      <p>
        Both formats describe the same data model (mostly), so converting is usually a 4-line script. In Python:
      </p>
      <pre><code>{`# pip install pyyaml
import json, yaml

with open("config.yaml") as f:
    data = yaml.safe_load(f)

with open("config.json", "w") as f:
    json.dump(data, f, indent=2)`}</code></pre>
      <p>
        For one-off conversion in the browser, the <a href="/tools/json-to-yaml">JSON ↔ YAML converter</a> on
        JSONKit handles both directions client-side — your data never leaves the browser.
      </p>

      <h2>Bottom line</h2>
      <p>
        JSON and YAML are not competitors so much as complements. Use JSON for wires and machines, YAML for
        configs and humans. When in doubt, pick the one that matches who is writing the file most often.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>
